ce:section.ce:para:
Curiosity about the feasibility of integration of SnS2 with the g-C3N4/C, herein, we directionally design a raspberry-like SnS2/g-C3N4/C (SCC) Z-scheme heterojunction using a biomass of mabospores as carbon source (
                        Fig. S1 and S2
                     ). As the support material, the mabospores-derived hollow carbon spheres play important role in the following aspects: increase the contact area of the semiconductor (SnS2/g-C3N4) with light for more active sites, adsorb more CO2 for reaction, accelerate the transfer of photogenerated charge carriers for low recombination, and subsequently improve the efficiency of CO2 photoreduction. Owing to the formation of Z-scheme heterojunction, the redox capacities of both SnS2 and g-C3N4 in the SCC are effectively promoted, which has been confirmed by an electron spin resonance (ESR) investigation. Meanwhile, density functional theory (DFT) calculations of the reaction pathways in combination with the experimental results reveal that the hollow spherical SCC Z-scheme heterojunction can interact more strongly with CO2 molecules and the reaction intermediates, and effectively reduce the reaction energy barrier in favor of CO2 photoreduction. This work demonstrates a representative indication in Z-scheme-induced enhancement on photocatalytic activity for g-C3N4 with the assistance of a second semiconductor and distinctive morphological biomass-derived carbon as electron-conducting channels.

Stannic chloride pentahydrate (SnCl4·5H2O, AR), melamine (C3H6N6, AR), and potassium hydroxide (KOH, AR) were supported by Aladdin Chemistry Co., Ltd. Concentrated hydrochloric acid (HCl, 37 wt%, AR) and thiourea (CH4N2S, AR) were purchased from Sinopharm Chemical Reagent Co., Ltd. Fresh mabospores with hollow spherical morphology stripped from biomass puffballs (
                           Fig. S1
                        ) were used to as carbon source and purchased from China Pharmaceutical Co., Ltd. Deionized water was used to prepare different solutions and rinse samples.

Fig. 2 exhibits the SEM image and the corresponding EDS line scan of SCC. It can be seen in Fig. 2 a that the SCC presents uniformly spherical structure (carbon sphere) inherited from the spore precursor with an average diameter of ∼ 2.5 μm. In the magnified image of a single carbon sphere (Fig. 2 b and 2c), a large amount of particles loaded on the sphere can be found, which exhibits a rough surface, and numerous nanosheets assigned to g-C3N4 and SnS2 are observed to be highly-distributed on the whole sphere (Fig. 2 d). Evidently, the SCC possesses the ideal hollow sphere morphology like a raspberry, which is beneficial to increase the multiple reflection of light in the channel and promote the absorption of light. Further magnified SEM image reveals the irregular nanosheet structure of g-C3N4 and hexagonal nanosheet-structure of SnS2 on the surface of carbon sphere (
Fig. S5
). To grasp the element distributions in detail, an EDS line scan (from point A to B) for elements of C, N, Sn, S (Fig. 2 e, 2f, S6 and S7) are measured and the results show that four elements are highly dispersed on the SCC, which enables the full contact of constitutive g-C3N4 and SnS2 with light to produce more photogenerated charge carriers for potential improvement of photocatalytic activity. Fig. 3 illustrates the representative TEM images of SCC. One can observe that g-C3N4 and SnS2 nanosheets are loaded on the surface of carbon sphere without obvious aggregations (Fig. 3 a). Some of them are stacked together (Fig. 3 c), while others are staggered (Fig. 3 d). The HRTEM image in Fig. 3 e depicts two crystal planes of (101) for SnS2 and (002) for g-C3N4 with the characteristic lattice spacing of 0.246 and 0.344 nm, respectively [35]. Meanwhile, the SAED diagram (Fig. 3 f) shows that the (002), (100) and (100) crystal planes of SnS2 are associated with different diffraction rings, respectively, which means it belongs to polycrystalline structure [36]. These are consistent well with the XRD result for SCC. Additionally, the element mapping observations confirm that four elements are highly dispersed on the SCC (Fig. 3 g-3 l).
